s</i>, which, with its variants and cognates, is one of the commonest personal names in Europe. Spellings with <i>-h-</i>, which first appear in English in the 16th century and in French (as <i>Anthoine</i>) at about the same time, are due to the erroneous belief that the name derives from Greek <i>anthos</i> ‘flower’. The popularity of the personal name in Christendom is largely due to the cult of the Egyptian hermit Saint Anthony (  AD  251–356), who in his old age gathered a community of hermits around him, and for that reason is regarded by some as the founder of monasticism. It was further increased by the fame of Saint Anthony of Padua (1195–1231), who long enjoyed a great popular cult and who is believed to help people find lost things. In North America, the English form of the surname has absorbed cognates and derivatives (patronymics) from other languages, for example Greek patronymic   Antoniades  , Italian   Antoni  , Polish   Antoniewicz  , Croatian and Serbian <b>Antonović</b> (see   Antonovich  ) and <b>Antunović</b>; see also below. The name <i>Anthony</i> is also found among Christians in southern India, but since South Indians traditionally do not have hereditary surnames, the southern Indian name was in most cases registered as such only after immigration of its bearers to the US. Compare   Antony  .","German, Flemish, and French (mainly Alsace): Latinized (humanistic) patronymic from local equivalents of the Latin personal name <i>Antonius</i>, from its genitive form <i>Antoni(i)</i>. In North America, this surname is also an altered form of the German, Dutch, French, and Slovak cognates   Antoni   1 and   Antony   2.","History: John Anthony of Hampstead, Middlesex, England (now part of north London) migrated to Boston, MA, in 1634. By 1640 he had moved to Providence, RI, where his descendants are still established."]},{"name":"Antwine","meanings":["Americanized form of French   Antoine  ."]},{"name":"Danton","meanings":["French: habitational name, with fused preposition <i>d(e)</i> ‘from’, denoting someone from either of two places, in Isère and Haute-Savoie, called Anthon. This surname is also found in Britain, where it is of French Huguenot origin.","French: patronymic, with fused preposition <i>d(e)</i> ‘of’, from the personal name <i>Anton</i>, a variant of   Antoine  .","English (Kent): possibly from one of many places called Denton (e.g. near Alciston, Sussex), one of six places called <i>Dunton</i> (Bedfordshire, Buckinghamshire, Essex, Leicestershire, Norfolk, Warwickshire), or <i>Downton</i> (Gloucestershire, Wiltshire), or Taunton (Somerset). The later Kentish surname may be connected with Danton Farm in Cheriton (Kent), this being a late form of the farm name <i>Dalmington</i>."]},{"name":"Antoinette","meanings":["French: from the female personal name <i>Antoinette</i>, feminine form of   Antoine  , an equivalent of   Anthony  ."]}]},{"name":"Odile","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the medieval Germanic name <i>Odila</i>, a derivative of <i>od</i> meaning ‘prosperity, wealth’; borne by a 8th-century saint who founded a Benedictine convent at what is now Odilienburg in Alsace; she is the patron saint of Alsace."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Odile ANTOINE was born as the daughter of Jean ANTOINE and Marguerite NN. She married Demange Hanzo in 1648. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter."},"et":{"–":"Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1620–1686":"1620–1686","1645–1704":"1645–1704","1645–Female":"1645–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1645":"1645","um 1648":"1648","1686":"1686","1620":"1620","ABT 1645":"umbes 1645","1704":"1704","Plaine, Bas-Rhin, Grand Est, France":"Plaine, Bas-Rhin, Grand Est, Prantsusmaa","Saint Blaine la Roche, Elsaß-Lothringen, Frankreich":"Alsace, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"–":"Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1620–1686":"1620–1686","1645–1704":"1645–1704","1645–Female":"1645–Kuollut","–Ma